- <p>Captain Nemo was compelled, therefore, to remain. He observed these men thrown
  without resources upon a desert island, but had no wish to be himself discovered
  by them. By degrees he became interested in their efforts when he saw them honest,
  energetic, and bound to each other by the ties of friendship. As if despite his
  wishes, he penetrated all the secrets of their existence. By means of the diving
  dress he could easily reach the well in the interior of Granite House, and climbing
  by the projections of rock to its upper orifice he heard the colonists as they recounted
  the past, and studied the present and future. He learned from them the tremendous
  conflict of America with America itself, for the abolition of slavery. Yes, these
  men were worthy to reconcile Captain Nemo with that humanity which they represented
  so nobly in the island.</p>
- <p>Captain Nemo had saved Cyrus Harding. It was he also who had brought back the
  dog to the Chimneys, who rescued Top from the waters of the lake, who caused to
  fall at Flotsam Point the case containing so many things useful to the colonists,
